# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cue-sports
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cue-sports/2001-world-games] The **2001 World Games** (Japanese: 2001年ワールドゲームズ, romanized: *2001-Nen wārudogēmuzu*), the sixth World Games, were an international multi-sport event held in Akita, Japan.
[src:cue-sports/2001-world-games] 140 titles (invitational sports not included) were awarded in the following official sports.
[src:cue-sports/2001-world-games] There were five invitational sports in this edition.
[src:cue-sports/2001-world-games] The 2001 World Games programme featured 27 official sports and 4 invitational sports.
[src:cue-sports/2001-world-games] (Aikido was deemed a demonstration sport; no medal events were held.) The numbers in parentheses indicate the number of medal events that were contested in each sports discipline.
[src:cue-sports/2001-world-games] The results from the 2001 World Games are from the archived website of the Akita, Japan, organizing committee.
[src:cue-sports/2001-world-games] The medal tally during the sixth World Games is as follows.
[src:cue-sports/2001-world-games] Russia finished at the top of the final medal table.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Acrobatic gymnasts perform in one of five units: pairs (same-gender or mixed) or same-gender groups (three for women, four for men).
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] In each partnership, the gymnasts' different sizes and abilities will be balanced to complement each other in order to carry out the complex moves.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Some will mainly carry out supporting and pitching roles and are known as bases.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] They are then balanced with usually smaller gymnasts who become the 'tops'.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] In men's and women's groups there are also one or two 'middles', who are like another base who usually will support the top while balancing on the base.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] In competition, partnerships perform a routine to music, which has usually been choreographed specifically for them.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The gymnasts carry out their acrobatic moves and combine them with dance, all in time to and in keeping with the style of the music.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Partnerships are judged on artistry/dance, execution of skills, and difficulty of skills, with the scoring emphasis on execution.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The rules for the sport, known as the Code of Points, are governed by the FIG.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] These rules are subject to change every four years in line with the Olympic cycle, as in other disciplines of gymnastics.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Acrobatics have a long history dating back thousands of years across the world and appeared in festivals, early circuses, and later vaudeville acts as a form of entertainment.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The first use of acrobatics as a specific sport was in the Soviet Union in the 1930s, though its development was interrupted by the World War II.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The first competition, for men only, was held in 1939, with a women's event being added the next year.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] In 1957, the first international competition was held between the Soviet Union, Poland, Bulgaria, and East Germany.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The International Federation of Sports Acrobatics was established in 1973, and the first world championships were held in 1974.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The federation dissolved in 1998, and acrobatic gymnastics was from then on governed by the FIG.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] It was originally called **sports acrobatics** but has been known as **acrobatic gymnastics** since 2007.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] In addition to the current five categories, two additional categories for tumbling (men's and women's) were included until the 1999 World Championships, though some groups still involve tumbling events.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] In the United States, the first national sports acrobatics organization was called the United States Sports Acrobatics Federation (USSAF).
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Founded in 1975, its name was changed to the United States Sports Acrobatics (USSA) in the 1990s.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The USSA then merged with USA Gymnastics in 2002, and acrobatic gymnastics is now a discipline therein.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] For example, the 28th Acrobatic Gymnastics European Championships were held in Rzeszów, Poland, in October 2017.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] There are also numerous national, state, and regional competitions that are held in each country.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Local and regional competitions often form the qualification stages required to compete at national championships.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] There is no requirement from the FIG for gymnasts to have qualified through their own national championships to compete internationally, but local governing bodies will often make their national team selections based on performance at national competition.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] At the London 2012 Olympics, acrobatic partnerships were seen performing before the Olympic gymnastics' events, and during the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gold, silver, and bronze medals are generally awarded in the usual fashion, although in some competitions, a minimum score is required to qualify for medals.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasts may only participate in one level and unit (pair or group) at a competition.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The number of required routines at a competition depends on the level at which the gymnasts are competing.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] At the junior and senior levels, all three routines mentioned below are required.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] At lower age levels, only a single simpler routine is required.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Each of the routine types has a different emphasis, but all include tumbling and dance as elements.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Dynamic (formerly known as Tempo) – These routines demonstrate power, strength and grace through the performance of acrobatic moves that involve the phases of spring, flight, rotation, and landing.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] This often involves the base, or bases in the partnership propelling the top through the air and through a series of somersaults or twists.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The top is generally caught or supported in the landing by their base(s).
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Dynamic routines last approximately two minutes.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Combined – At the more senior levels of competition (11–19 through senior levels), a third routine must be performed that combines both balance and dynamic moves, along with the usual tumbling and dance (tumbling is not required from senior level athletes).
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Typically, it is performed as a final's routine, with a duration, depending upon the level of competition, of approximately 2 minutes and 30 seconds.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] As in artistic gymnastics, compulsory routines, consisting of a prescribed sequence of elements, were previously required along with optional routines, consisting of elements chosen by the gymnasts and their coaches, although this is no longer the case at the highest level of the sport.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The final score of a routine is the sum of the **difficulty**, **execution**, and **artistry** scores, minus any additional penalties incurred.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] For seniors, the difficulty score is open-ended with no maximum, while the execution and artistry scores have a starting value of 10 points and are lowered for specific mistakes made by the gymnasts.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Emphasis is put on the execution score, which is doubled to provide the final score.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Difficulty is the sum of the difficulty value assigned to each element the gymnasts perform during an exercise.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Senior gymnasts have no difficulty limit.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasts submit a 'tariff sheet' listing their planned elements ahead of the competition.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Execution is the degree to which the gymnasts performs an element with aesthetic and technical perfection.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Execution penalties are subtracted from the starting score of 10 and concern aspects such as the amplitude of flight elements, correctness of body shapes, and controlled landings.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Penalties range from 0.1 for small mistakes, such as a small bend at the waist in a handstand, to 0.5 for large ones.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] A top falling rather than being caught by a partner is a one-point deduction.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Artistry evaluates the relationship of the gymnasts with each other and the music, the choreography of the routine, and the variety displayed in a routine.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The choreography of the routine use the whole floor and flow logically from one element to the next, gymnasts should display emotion throughout the performance and perform well with each other, and the choreography should show creativity and original elements.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Penalties are deducted from the final score.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] In 1978, each element was evaluated as either a Group 1 element or Group 2 element, with Group 1 elements being worth 0.4 difficulty points and Group 2 elements being worth 0.2.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] A routine required at least five elements, at least three of which were required to be Group 2 elements.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The minimum difficulty level started a routine at 9.0 points, with the maximum being 10.0.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] For the 2025–2028 code, changes were made to encourage variety and allow for mixed series of balance and dynamic elements while keeping the code relatively stable for the benefit of countries where acrobatic gymnastics is still developing.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] The judging panels of acrobatic gymnastics are similar to other disciplines of gymnastics where different panels of judges are overseen by a head judge, and each panel has a 'Chair of the Judging Panel' (CJP) who oversees that panel's activities.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasts train new elements with plenty of safety mats as well as safety harnesses, which are also called spotting belts.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasiums must have a high ceiling to make sure gymnasts at the top of pyramids or being thrown high in the air do not hit the ceiling.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] To support a grip on the head, bases will often keep their hair short or shave the area gripped by a top, and they may use chalk to assist the top's grip.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Most acrobatic gymnastics injuries occur in the lower limbs, such as to the knee and ankle, with wrist injuries also being relatively frequent.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Ligament injuries are common, though one study found a sex difference, with female gymnasts most frequently having ligament injuries while male gymnasts were most likely to have tendon injuries.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] Bases are more frequently injured than tops, and tops are more prone to acute injuries such as fractures or sprains, while bases are more prone to overuse injuries.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] As in other gymnastics disciplines, disordered eating is a concern, although it is not well-studied in acrobatic gymnastics in particular.
[src:cue-sports/acrobatic-gymnastics] One study surveyed female gymnasts aged 10–19 participating in a World Cup event for indicators of disordered eating; they found that older gymnasts, gymnasts acting as bases, and gymnasts from Eastern Europe were at higher risk of disordered eating behaviors.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] The performance area is a floor 10 metres (33 ft) square.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Trio, groups, and aerobic dance and step groups may consist of gymnasts of any combination of genders.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Gymnasts frequently compete in more than one competition category at the same competition and are allowed to compete in up to three at the World Championships.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] All routines last for 1 minute and 20 to 30 seconds.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Women must wear a leotard with tights or a full-length unitard, and men must wear either a form-fitting top with shorts or pants or a full-length unitard.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Men are not permitted to have sequins or long sleeves on their competition costume.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] For individual, pairs, trio, and group routines, scores have three components: **difficulty**, **execution**, and **artistry**, which are added together to create the final score.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] For dance and step routines, scores only consist of artistry and execution scores.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Individual routines consist of eight elements; performing more elements incurs a deduction.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Elements include dynamic strength elements such as pushup variations and leg circles, static strength elements like planches that may be performed while turning on the hands, jumps, turns, and splits.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Limited acrobatic elements such as handsprings are allowed as well.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Up to three elements may be performed in combination with each other for a connection bonus.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Gymnasts must perform a variety of elements during their routines.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Individual men must perform a dynamic leap element and may not perform flexibility or balance elements, while individual women must perform a turn.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Pairs, trios, and groups must perform the same elements simultaneously and show multiple instances of two or more people working together in a collaborative movement.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] The **difficulty score** is calculated by adding together the difficulty values of the performed elements, then dividing by a different divisor depending on the competition category, and for trios and groups, gender makeup.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] For example, the difficulty a group routine performed by five men will be divided by 2, that of a mixed-gender group by 1.9, and that of an all-women group by 1.8.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] The **execution score** begins at 10 points, and deductions are taken for wrong technique or mistakes.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] For pairs, trios, and groups, the worst performance of an element across all gymnasts is used to take deductions.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] The **artistry score** has a maximum of 10 points.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Routines are evaluated a variety of criteria, such as creativity, musicality and music composition, quality of aerobic movement patterns, use of space, and performance quality.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Aerobic gymnastics stems from the aerobics trend of the 1980s, which spawned competitions.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] The first national aerobic championships were held in the United States in 1984, organized by Howard and Karen Schwartz, who took aerobics from a fitness activity and developed it into a competitive discipline.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] They also organized the first (pre-FIG) World championships in 1990, with 16 participating countries, and the first World Youth Aerobic Championship in 1998, with specific divisions for athletes aged between 8 and 17 years.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] In 1993, various national federations approached the FIG to request it be included as a gymnastics discipline.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] A Code of Points was developed; the first edition was only 20 pages.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] In 1995, the FIG recognised sport aerobics as a new competitive gymnastics discipline, organised judges and coaches courses and launched the first Aerobic Gymnastics World Championships in Paris, with 34 countries sending competitors.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] In 1997, the IWGA (International World Games Association) included Aerobic Gymnastics in the 5th World Games (Lahti, Finland).
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Since 1999, the European Union of Gymnastics has been conducting Aerobic European Gymnastics Championships in every odd year.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] By 2015, 75 national federations participated in aerobic gymnastics.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] As in other gymnastics disciplines such as rhythmic gymnastics, athletes may feel pressured to be thin, especially for athletes with a higher body mass index, even if they are quite thin by typical standards.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] Pressure to lose weight can come from parents, coaches, peers, and other gymnastics authority figures such as judges, and it can lead to disordered eating behaviors.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] A study of athletes competing at the 2022 World Championships found that those who participated in the study trained an average of 16 to 18 hours a week.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] 73% of participants reported an injury occurring in the previous year.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] The most common injuries were muscle strains, tears, and ruptures as well as sprains.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] The legs, especially the ankle, knee, and foot, were the most commonly injured areas, followed by the shoulders, wrists, and hands in the upper body, followed by the hip and spine.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] More than half of the participants also reported significant stress.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] In the American sketch comedy television series Key & Peele, the duo parodies the '80s video footage of the National Aerobic Championship in a sketch showing one of the aerobic dancers experiencing a meltdown while dancing to the championship theme song.
[src:cue-sports/aerobic-gymnastics] In the Mannrobics taunt in the video game Team Fortress 2, the Alternate-Fire action resembles some moves done in the 1988 Crystal Light National Aerobic Championship.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] It was originally developed by Morihei Ueshiba, as a synthesis of his martial studies, philosophy and religious beliefs.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Ueshiba's goal was to create an art which practitioners could use to defend themselves against attacks, while also protecting the attackers from injury.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido is often translated as "the way of unifying (with) life energy" or as "the way of harmonious spirit".
[src:cue-sports/aikido] According to the founder's philosophy, the primary goal in the practice of aikido is to overcome oneself instead of cultivating violence or aggressiveness.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Morihei Ueshiba used the phrase *"masakatsu agatsu katsuhayabi"* (正勝吾勝勝速日, "true victory, final victory over oneself, here and now") to refer to this principle.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido's fundamental principles include: *irimi* (entering), *atemi* (strikes), *kokyu-ho* (breathing control), *sankaku-ho* (triangular principle), and *tenkan* (turning) movements which redirect the opponent's attack momentum.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Its curriculum comprises various techniques, primarily throws and joint locks.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] It includes a weapons system encompassing the *bokken*, *tantō*, and *jō*.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido derives mainly from the martial art of Daitō-ryū Aiki-jūjutsu, but began to diverge from it in the late 1920s, partly due to Ueshiba's involvement with the Ōmoto-kyō religion.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Ueshiba's early students' documents bear the term *aiki-jūjutsu*.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Ueshiba's senior students have different approaches to aikido, depending partly on when they studied with him.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Today, aikido is found all over the world in a number of styles, with broad ranges of interpretation and emphasis.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] However they all share techniques formulated by Ueshiba and most have concern for the well-being of the attacker.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The term *aiki* does not readily appear in the Japanese language outside the scope of budō.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] This has led to many possible interpretations of the word. 合 (*Ai*) is mainly used in compounds to mean 'combine, unite, join, meet', examples being 合同 (combined/united), 合成 (composition), 結合 (unite/combine/join), 連合 (union/alliance/association), 統合 (combine/unify), and 合意 (mutual agreement).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] There is an idea of reciprocity, 知り合う (to get to know one another), 話し合い (talk/discussion/negotiation), and 待ち合わせる (meet by appointment).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The term *dō* in Aikido is found in many other Japanese martial arts such as, judo and kendo, and in various non-martial arts, such as Japanese calligraphy (*shodō*), flower arranging (*kadō*) and tea ceremony (*chadō* or *sadō*).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Therefore, from a purely literal interpretation, aikido is the "Way of combining forces" or "Way of unifying energy", in which the term *aiki* refers to the martial arts principle or tactic of blending with an attacker's movements for the purpose of controlling their actions with minimal effort.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] One applies *aiki* by understanding the rhythm and intent of the attacker to find the optimal position and timing to apply a counter-technique.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido was created by Morihei Ueshiba (植芝 盛平) (1883–1969), referred to by some aikido practitioners as *Ōsensei* (*Great Teacher*).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The term *aikido* was coined in the 20th century.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Ueshiba envisioned aikido not only as the synthesis of his martial training, but as an expression of his personal philosophy of universal peace and reconciliation.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] During Ueshiba's lifetime and continuing today, aikido has evolved from the *aiki* that Ueshiba studied into a variety of expressions by martial artists throughout the world.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Ueshiba developed aikido primarily during the late 1920s through the 1930s through the synthesis of the older martial arts that he had studied.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The core martial art from which aikido derives is Daitō-ryū Aiki-jūjutsu, which Ueshiba studied directly with Takeda Sōkaku, the reviver of that art.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Additionally, Ueshiba is known to have studied Tenjin Shin'yō-ryū with Tozawa Tokusaburō in Tokyo in 1901, Gotōha Yagyū Shingan-ryū under Nakai Masakatsu in Sakai from 1903 to 1908, and judo with Kiyoichi Takagi (高木 喜代市) (1894–1972) in Tanabe in 1911.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The art of *Daitō-ryū* is the primary technical influence on aikido.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Along with empty-handed throwing and joint-locking techniques, Ueshiba incorporated training movements with weapons, such as those for the spear (*yari*), short staff (*jō*), and possibly the bayonet (銃剣, *jūken*).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido also derives much of its technical structure from the art of swordsmanship (*kenjutsu*).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Ueshiba moved to Hokkaido in 1912, and began studying under Takeda Sokaku in 1915; His official association with Daitō-ryū continued until 1937.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] However, during the latter part of that period, Ueshiba had already begun to distance himself from Takeda and the *Daitō-ryū*.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] At that time Ueshiba referred to his martial art as "**Aiki Budō**".
[src:cue-sports/aikido] It is unclear exactly when Ueshiba began using the name "aikido", but it became the official name of the art in 1942 when the Greater Japan Martial Virtue Society (*Dai Nippon Butoku Kai*) was engaged in a government sponsored reorganization and centralization of Japanese martial arts.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] After Ueshiba left Hokkaido in 1919, he met and was profoundly influenced by Onisaburo Deguchi, the spiritual leader of the Ōmoto-kyō religion (a neo-Shinto movement) in Ayabe.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] One of the primary features of Ōmoto-kyō is its emphasis on the attainment of utopia during one's life.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The idea was a great influence on Ueshiba's martial arts philosophy of extending love and compassion especially to those who seek to harm others.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido demonstrates this philosophy in its emphasis on mastering martial arts so that one may receive an attack and harmlessly redirect it.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In an ideal resolution, not only is the receiver unharmed, but so is the attacker.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In addition to the effect on his spiritual growth, the connection with Deguchi gave Ueshiba entry to elite political and military circles as a martial artist.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] As a result of the exposure, he was able to attract not only financial backing but also gifted students.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Several of the students went on to begin their own styles of aikido.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido was first introduced to the rest of the world in 1951 by Minoru Mochizuki with a visit to France, where he demonstrated aikido techniques to judo students.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] He was followed by Tadashi Abe in 1952, who came as the official Aikikai Hombu representative, remaining in France for seven years.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Kenji Tomiki toured with a delegation of various martial arts through 15 continental states of the United States in 1953.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Later in the same year, Koichi Tohei was sent by Aikikai Hombu to Hawaii for a full year, where he set up several dōjō.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The trip was followed by several visits and is considered the formal introduction of aikido to the United States.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The United Kingdom followed in 1955; Italy in 1964 by Hiroshi Tada; and Germany in 1965 by Katsuaki Asai.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Designated the "Official Delegate for Europe and Africa" by Morihei Ueshiba, Masamichi Noro arrived in France in September 1961.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Seiichi Sugano was appointed to introduce aikido to Australia in 1965.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Today there are aikido dōjō throughout the world.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Steven Seagal's film debut *Above the Law* (1988) is regarded as the first American film to feature aikido in fight sequences.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The largest aikido organization is the Aikikai Foundation, which remains under the control of the Ueshiba family.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] However, aikido has developed into many styles, most of which were formed by Morihei Ueshiba's major students.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The earliest independent styles to emerge were Yoseikan Aikido, begun by Minoru Mochizuki in 1931, Yoshinkan Aikido, founded by Gozo Shioda in 1955, and Shodokan Aikido, founded by Kenji Tomiki in 1967.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The emergence of these styles pre-dated Ueshiba's death and did not cause any major upheavals when they were formalized.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Shodokan Aikido, however, was controversial, since it introduced a unique rule-based competition that some felt was contrary to the spirit of aikido.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] After Ueshiba's death in 1969, two more major styles emerged.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Significant controversy arose with the departure of the Aikikai Hombu Dojo's chief instructor Koichi Tohei, in 1974.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Tohei left as a result of a disagreement with the son of the founder, Kisshomaru Ueshiba, who at that time headed the Aikikai Foundation.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The disagreement was over the proper role of *ki* development in regular aikido training.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] After Tohei left, he formed his own style, called Shin Shin Toitsu Aikido, and the organization that governs it, the Ki Society (*Ki no Kenkyūkai*).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] A final major style evolved from Ueshiba's retirement in Iwama, Ibaraki and the teaching methodology of long term student Morihiro Saito.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] It is unofficially referred to as the "Iwama style", and at one point a number of its followers formed a loose network of schools they called Iwama Ryu.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Although Iwama style practitioners remained part of the Aikikai until Saito's death in 2002, followers of Saito subsequently split into two groups.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] One remained with the Aikikai and the other formed the independent Shinshin Aikishuren Kai in 2004 around Saito's son Hitohiro Saito.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Today, the major styles of aikido are each run by a separate governing organization, have their own headquarters (本部道場, *honbu dōjō*) in Japan, and are taught throughout the world.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The study of *ki* is an important component of aikido.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The term does not specifically refer to either physical or mental training, as it encompasses both.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The kanji for *ki* was written in its older form as 氣 up until the Japanese governmental writing reforms after World War II, and now is more prevalently seen in its modern form of 気.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] This form has the removal of the eight directions denoting the pre and post natal energies of *genki* (元氣) (Chinese – *yuán qì*) also known in the Art of Aikido as "Source energy".
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The character for *ki* is used in everyday Japanese terms, such as "health" (元気, *genki*), or "shyness" (内気, *uchiki*).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] *Ki* has many meanings, including "ambience", "mind", "mood", or "intention and action", although its literal meaning is 'air' or 'breath'.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] However, in traditional martial arts and medicine it is often referred to in its more general terminology as "life energy".
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Gozo Shioda's Yoshinkan Aikido, considered one of the "hard styles", largely follows Ueshiba's teachings from before World War II, and surmises that the secret to *ki* lies in timing and the application of the whole body's strength to a single point.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In later years, Ueshiba's application of *ki* in aikido took on a softer, more gentle feel.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The concept was known as Takemusu Aiki, and many of his later students teach about *ki* from this perspective.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Koichi Tohei's Ki Society centers almost exclusively around the study of the empirical (albeit subjective) experience of *ki*, with students' proficiency in aikido techniques and *ki* development ranked separately.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In aikido, as in virtually all Japanese martial arts, there are both physical and mental aspects of training.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The physical training in aikido is diverse, covering both general physical fitness and conditioning, as well as specific techniques.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Because a substantial portion of any aikido curriculum consists of throws, beginners learn how to safely fall or roll.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The specific techniques for attack include both strikes and grabs; the techniques for defense consist of throws and pins.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] After basic techniques are learned, students study freestyle defense against multiple opponents, and techniques with weapons.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In some dojo, Uchi-deshi programs permit students to live in the dojo and immerse themselves in practice several times each day.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Physical training goals pursued in conjunction with aikido include controlled relaxation, correct movement of joints such as hips and shoulders, flexibility, and endurance, with less emphasis on strength training.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In aikido, pushing or extending movements are much more common than pulling or contracting movements.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] This distinction can be applied to general fitness goals for the aikido practitioner.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In aikido, specific muscles or muscle groups are not isolated and worked to improve tone, mass, or power.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido-related training emphasizes the use of coordinated whole-body movement and balance similar to yoga or pilates.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] For example, many dōjōs begin each class with warm-up exercises (準備体操, *junbi taisō*), which may include stretching and *ukemi* (break falls).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido training is based primarily on two partners practicing pre-arranged forms (*kata*) rather than freestyle practice.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Both halves of the technique, that of *uke* and that of *tori*, are considered essential to aikido training.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Both are studying aikido principles of blending and adaptation.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] *Tori* learns to blend with and control attacking energy, while *uke* learns to become calm and flexible in the disadvantageous, off-balance positions in which *tori* places them.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] This "receiving" of the technique is called *ukemi*.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] *Uke* continuously seeks to regain balance and cover vulnerabilities (e.g., an exposed side), while *tori* uses position and timing to keep *uke* off-balance and vulnerable.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In more advanced training, *uke* will sometimes apply reversal techniques (返し技, *kaeshi-waza*) to regain balance and pin or throw *tori*.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] *Ukemi* (受身) refers to the act of receiving a technique.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Good *ukemi* involves attention to the technique, the partner, and the immediate environment—it is considered an active part of the process of learning aikido.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The method of falling itself is also important, and is a way for the practitioner to receive an aikido technique safely and minimize risk of injury.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido techniques are usually a defense against an attack, so students must learn to deliver various types of attacks to be able to practice aikido with a partner.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Although attacks are not studied as thoroughly as in striking-based arts, attacks with intent (such as a strong strike or an immobilizing grab) are needed to study correct and effective application of technique.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Many of the strikes (打ち, *uchi*) of aikido resemble cuts from a sword or other grasped object, which indicate its origins in techniques intended for armed combat.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Other techniques which explicitly appear to be punches (*tsuki*), are practiced as thrusts with a knife or sword.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Kicks are generally reserved for upper-level variations; reasons cited include that falls from kicks are especially dangerous, and that kicks (high kicks in particular) were uncommon during the types of combat prevalent in feudal Japan.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Beginners in particular often practice techniques from grabs, both because they are safer and because it is easier to feel the energy and the direction of the movement of force of a hold than it is for a strike.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Some grabs are historically derived from being held while trying to draw a weapon, whereupon a technique could then be used to free oneself and immobilize or strike the attacker while they are grabbing the defender.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Here is a sample of the basic or widely practiced throws and pins.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Many of the techniques derive from Daitō-ryū Aiki-jūjutsu, but some others were invented by Morihei Ueshiba.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The precise terminology for some may vary between organisations and styles; the terms presented are the terms used by the Aikikai Foundation.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Although the names of the first five techniques listed are in succession, they are not universally taught in numeric order.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido makes use of body movement (*tai sabaki* or 体捌き) to blend the movement of *tori* with the movement of *uke*.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] For example, an "entering" (*irimi*) technique consists of movements inward towards *uke*, while a "turning" (転換, *tenkan*) technique uses a pivoting motion.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Finally, most techniques can be performed while in a seated posture (*seiza*).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Techniques where both *uke* and *tori* are standing are called *tachi-waza*, techniques where both start off in *seiza* are called *suwari-waza*, and techniques performed with *uke* standing and *tori* sitting are called *hanmi handachi* (半身半立).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] From these few basic techniques, there are numerous of possible implementations.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] For example, *ikkyō* can be applied to an opponent moving forward with a strike (perhaps with an *ura* type of movement to redirect the incoming force), or to an opponent who has already struck and is now moving back to reestablish distance (perhaps an *omote-waza* version).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Specific aikido *kata* are typically referred to with the formula "attack-technique(-modifier)"; *katate-dori ikkyō*, for example, refers to any *ikkyō* technique executed when *uke* is holding one wrist.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] This could be further specified as *katate-dori ikkyō omote* (referring to any forward-moving *ikkyō* technique from that grab).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Weapons training in aikido traditionally includes the short staff (*jō*) (these techniques closely resemble the use of the bayonet, or Jūkendō), the wooden sword (*bokken*), and the knife (*tantō*).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Some schools incorporate firearm-disarming techniques, where either weapon-taking and/or weapon-retention may be taught.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Some schools, such as the Iwama style of Morihiro Saito, usually spend substantial time practicing with both *bokken* and *jō*, under the names of *aiki-ken*, and *aiki-jō*, respectively.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The founder developed many of the empty-handed techniques from traditional sword, spear and bayonet movements.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Consequently, the practice of the weapons arts gives insight into the origin of techniques and movements, and reinforces the concepts of distance, timing, foot movement, presence and connectedness with one's training partner(s).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] One feature of aikido is training to defend against multiple attackers, often called *taninzudori*, or *taninzugake*.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Freestyle practice with multiple attackers called *randori* (乱取) is a key part of most curricula and is required for the higher-level ranks.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] *Randori* exercises a person's ability to intuitively perform techniques in an unstructured environment.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Strategic choice of techniques, based on how they reposition the student relative to other attackers, is important in *randori* training.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] For instance, an *ura* technique might be used to neutralise the current attacker while turning to face attackers approaching from behind.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In Shodokan Aikido, *randori* differs in that it is not performed with multiple persons with defined roles of defender and attacker, but between two people, where both participants attack, defend, and counter at will.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In this respect it resembles judo *randori*.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In applying a technique during training, it is the responsibility of *tori* to prevent injury to *uke* by employing a speed and force of application that is appropriate with their partner's proficiency in *ukemi*.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] When injuries (especially to the joints) occur, they are often the result of a *tori* misjudging the ability of *uke* to receive the throw or pin.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] A study of injuries in the martial arts showed that the type of injuries varied considerably from one art to the other.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Soft tissue injuries are one of the most common types of injuries found within aikido, as well as joint strain and stubbed fingers and toes.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Several deaths from head-and-neck injuries, caused by aggressive *shihōnage* in a *senpai/kōhai* hazing context, have been reported.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido training is mental as well as physical, emphasizing the ability to relax the mind and body even under the stress of dangerous situations.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] This is necessary to enable the practitioner to perform the 'enter-and-blend' movements that underlie aikido techniques, wherein an attack is met with confidence and directness.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Morihei Ueshiba once remarked that one "must be willing to receive 99% of an opponent's attack and stare death in the face" in order to execute techniques without hesitation.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] As a martial art concerned not only with fighting proficiency but with the betterment of daily life, this mental aspect is of key importance to aikido practitioners.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido practitioners (commonly called *aikidōka* outside Japan) generally progress by promotion through a series of "grades" (*kyū*), followed by a series of "degrees" (*dan*), pursuant to formal testing procedures.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Some aikido organizations use belts to distinguish practitioners' grades, often simply white and black belts to distinguish *kyu* and *dan* grades, although some use various belt colors.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Testing requirements vary, so a particular rank in one organization is not comparable or interchangeable with the rank of another.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Some dōjōs have an age requirement before students can take the *dan* rank exam.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The uniform worn for practicing aikido (*aikidōgi*) is similar to the training uniform (*keikogi*) used in most other modern martial arts; simple trousers and a wraparound jacket, usually white.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Both thick ("judo-style"), and thin ("karate-style") cotton tops are used.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido-specific tops are available with shorter sleeves which reach to just below the elbow.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Most aikido systems add a pair of wide pleated black or indigo trousers known as *hakama* (used also in Naginatajutsu, kendo, and iaido).
[src:cue-sports/aikido] In many schools, the wearing of *hakama* is reserved for practitioners with *dan* ranks or for instructors, while others allow all practitioners to wear a *hakama* regardless of rank.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Aikido styles vary in their intention, due to its holistic nature.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] The most common differences noted in aikido, when observed externally, relate to the intensity and realism of training.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Stanley Pranin has observed that some criticism may stem from weak attacks from *uke*, allowing for a conditioned response from *tori*, resulting in underdevelopment of the skills needed for the safe and effective practice of both partners.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] To counteract that, some styles allow students to become less compliant over time.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] However, in keeping with the core philosophies, such allowance is granted only after having demonstrated proficiency in being able to protect themselves and their training partners.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Shodokan Aikido addresses the issue by practicing in a competitive format.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Such adaptations are debated between styles, with some maintaining that there is no need to adjust their methods because either the criticisms are unjustified, or that they are not training for self-defense or combat effectiveness, but spiritual, fitness or other reasons.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Reasons for the difference and diversity of teachings, intention, and forms of aikido can be traced to the shift in training focus after the end of Ueshiba's seclusion in Iwama from 1942 to the mid-1950s, as he increasingly emphasized the spiritual and philosophical aspects of aikido.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] As a result, strikes to vital points by *tori*, entering (*irimi*) and initiation of techniques by *tori*, the distinction between *omote* (front side) and *ura* (back side) techniques, and the use of weapons, were all de-emphasized or eliminated from practice.
[src:cue-sports/aikido] Conversely, some styles of aikido place less importance on the spiritual practices which were emphasized by Ueshiba.
[src:cue-sports/air-sports] The term "**air sports**" covers a range of aerial activities, including air racing, aerobatics, aeromodelling, hang gliding, human-powered aircraft, parachuting, paragliding, soaring, and skydiving.
[src:cue-sports/air-sports] Many air sports are regulated internationally by the Switzerland-based Fédération Aéronautique Internationale (FAI) and nationally by aero clubs such as the National Aeronautics Association (NAA) and the Royal Aero Club (RAeC).
[src:cue-sports/air-sports] The FAI has separate commissions for each air sport.
[src:cue-sports/air-sports] For example, the commission for ballooning is the Commission Internationale de l'Aérostation (CIA) and Federation of International Dronesoccer Association (FIDA).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] American football evolved in the United States, originating from the sports of soccer and rugby.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between two college teams, Rutgers and Princeton, using rules based on the rules of soccer at the time; by 1875, the sport had adopted rules similar to rugby union.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A set of rule changes drawn up from 1880 onward by Walter Camp, the "Father of American Football", established concepts that would define the sport, among them the snap, the line of scrimmage, eleven-player teams, and the concept of downs.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Later rule changes legalized the forward pass, created the neutral zone, and specified the size and shape of the football.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The modern sport is closely related to Canadian football, which evolved in parallel with and at the same time as the American game; the two sports are considered the primary variants of gridiron football.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] American football is the most popular sport in the United States; the most popular forms of the game are professional and college football, with the other major levels being high school and youth football.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Over a million Americans played college or high school football in 2022, and the National Football League (NFL) has one of the highest average attendance of any professional sports league in the world.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Its championship game, the Super Bowl, ranks among the most-watched club sporting events globally.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Other professional and amateur leagues exist worldwide, but the sport does not have the international popularity of other American sports like baseball or basketball; the sport maintains a growing following in the rest of North America, Europe, Brazil, and Japan.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Flag football, a variant of the sport, will be played at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In the United States, American football is referred to as "football".
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The term "football" was officially established in the rulebook for the 1876 college football season, when the sport first shifted from soccer-style rules to rugby-style rules.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Although it could easily have been called "rugby" at this point, Harvard, one of the primary proponents of the rugby-style game, compromised and did not request the name of the sport be changed to "rugby".
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The terms "gridiron" or "American football" are favored in English-speaking countries where other types of football are popular, such as the United Kingdom, Ireland, New Zealand, and Australia.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] American football evolved from the sports of rugby and soccer.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Rugby, like American football, is a sport in which two competing teams vie for control of a ball, which can be kicked through a set of goalposts or run into the opponent's goal area to score points.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] What is considered to be the first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between Rutgers and Princeton, two college teams.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] They consisted of 25 players per team and used a round ball that could not be picked up or carried.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] It could, however, be kicked or batted with the feet, hands, head, or sides, with the objective being to advance it into the opponent's goal.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Collegiate play continued for several years with games played using the rules of the host school.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Representatives of Yale, Columbia, Princeton and Rutgers met on October 19, 1873, to create a standard set of rules for use by all schools.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Teams were set at 20 players each, and fields of 400 by 250 feet (122 m × 76 m) were specified.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Harvard abstained from the conference, as they favored a rugby-style game that allowed running with the ball.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] An 1875 Harvard–Yale game played under rugby-style rules was observed by two Princeton athletes who were impressed by it.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] They introduced the sport to Princeton, a feat the Professional Football Researchers Association compared to "selling refrigerators to Eskimos".
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Princeton, Harvard, Yale, and Columbia then agreed to intercollegiate play using a form of rugby union rules with a modified scoring system.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] These schools formed the Intercollegiate Football Association, although Yale did not join until 1879.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Yale player Walter Camp, now regarded as the "Father of American Football", secured rule changes in 1880 that reduced the size of each team from 15 to 11 players and instituted the snap to replace the chaotic and inconsistent scrum.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] While the game between Rutgers and Princeton is commonly considered the first American football game, several years prior in 1862, the Oneida Football Club formed as the oldest known football club in the United States.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The team consisted of graduates of Boston's elite preparatory schools and played from 1862 to 1865.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The introduction of the snap resulted in an unexpected consequence.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Before the snap, the strategy had been to punt if a scrum resulted in a bad field position.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] However, a group of Princeton players realized that, as the snap was uncontested, they could now hold the ball indefinitely to prevent their opponent from scoring.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In 1881, in a game between Yale and Princeton, both teams used this strategy to maintain their undefeated records.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Each team held the ball, gaining no ground, for an entire half, resulting in a 0–0 tie.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] This "block game" proved extremely unpopular with both teams' spectators and fans.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A rule change was necessary to prevent this strategy from taking hold, and a reversion to the scrum was considered.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] However, Camp successfully proposed a rule in 1882 that limited each team to three downs, or tackles, to advance the ball 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Failure to advance the ball the required distance within those three downs would result in control of the ball being forfeited to the other team.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] This change effectively made American football a separate sport from rugby, and the resulting five-yard lines added to the field to measure distances made it resemble a gridiron in appearance.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Other major rule changes included a reduction of the field size to 110 by 53+1⁄3 yards (100.6 m × 48.8 m) and the adoption of a scoring system that awarded four points for a touchdown, two for a safety and a goal following a touchdown, and five for a goal from the field.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Additionally, tackling below the waist was legalized, and a static line of scrimmage was instituted.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Despite these new rules, football remained a violent sport.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Dangerous mass-formations like the flying wedge resulted in serious injuries and deaths.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A 1905 peak of 19 fatalities nationwide resulted in a threat by President Theodore Roosevelt to abolish the game unless major changes were made.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In response, 62 colleges and universities met in New York City to discuss rule changes on December 28, 1905.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] These proceedings resulted in the formation of the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States, later renamed the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The legal forward pass was introduced in 1906, although its effect was initially minimal due to the restrictions placed on its use.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The idea of a 40-yard-wider field was opposed by Harvard due to the size of the new Harvard Stadium.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Other rule changes introduced that year included the reduction of playing time from 70 to 60 minutes and an increase of the distance required for a first down from 5 to 10 yards (4.6 to 9.1 m).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] To reduce infighting and dirty play between teams, the neutral zone was created along the width of the football before the snap.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Scoring was also adjusted: points awarded for field goals were reduced to three in 1909 and points for touchdowns were raised to six in 1912.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Also in 1912, the field was shortened to 100 yards (91 m) long, two 10-yard-long (9.1 m) end zones were created, and teams were given four downs instead of three to advance the ball 10 yards (9.1 m).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The roughing the passer penalty was implemented in 1914, and eligible players were first allowed to catch the ball anywhere on the field in 1918.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] On November 12, 1892, Pudge Heffelfinger was paid $500 (equivalent to $17,917 in 2025) to play a game for the Allegheny Athletic Association against the Pittsburgh Athletic Club.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Despite these extra benefits, the game had a strict sense of amateurism at the time, and direct payment to players was frowned upon, if not prohibited outright.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Over time, professional play became increasingly common, and with it came rising salaries and unpredictable player movement, as well as the illegal payment of college players who were still in school.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The National Football League (NFL), a group of professional teams that was originally established in 1920 as the American Professional Football Association, aimed to solve these problems.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] This new league's stated goals included an end to bidding wars over players, prevention of the use of college players, and abolition of the practice of paying players to leave another team.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] By 1922, the NFL had established itself as America's premier professional football league.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The dominant form of football at the time was played at the collegiate level.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The upstart NFL received a boost to its legitimacy in 1925, however, when an NFL team, the Pottsville Maroons, defeated a team of Notre Dame all-stars in an exhibition game.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A greater emphasis on the passing game helped professional football to distinguish itself further from the college game during the late 1930s.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Football, in general, became increasingly popular following the 1958 NFL Championship game between the Baltimore Colts and the New York Giants, still referred to as the "Greatest Game Ever Played".
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The game, a 23–17 overtime victory by the Colts, was seen by millions of television viewers and had a major influence on the popularity of the sport.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] By the mid-1960s, football was the most popular sport in the United States.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In 1972, polling from Gallup, Inc. found that twice as many Americans identified football as their favorite sport (38%) as compared to baseball (19%); the sport has remained the most popular in the United States since.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In 1960, the American Football League (AFL) was created to compete with the NFL.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The AFL began in relative obscurity but eventually thrived, with an initial television contract with the ABC television network.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The AFL's existence forced the conservative NFL to expand to Dallas and Minnesota in an attempt to destroy the new league.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Meanwhile, the AFL introduced many new features to professional football in the United States and actively recruited minority players.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The AFL also signed several star college players who had also been drafted by NFL teams.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Competition for players heated up in 1965, when the AFL New York Jets signed rookie Joe Namath to a then-record $437,000 contract (equivalent to $4.46 million in 2024).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A five-year, $40 million NBC television contract followed, which helped to sustain the young league.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The bidding war for players ended in 1966 when NFL owners approached the AFL regarding a merger, and the two leagues agreed on one that took full effect in 1970.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] This agreement provided for a common draft that would take place each year, and it instituted an annual World Championship game to be played between the champions of each league.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] This championship game, which would come to be known as the Super Bowl, began play at the end of the 1966 season.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Once the merger was completed, it was no longer a championship game between two leagues, instead being competed between the American Football Conference (AFC) and the National Football Conference (NFC).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Prior to the 1956 college football season, NCAA schools were organized into an upper University Division and lower College Division.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In the summer of 1973, the University Division became Division I, but by 1976, there was a desire to further separate the major football programs from those that were less financially successful, while still allowing their other sports to compete at the top level.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In 1978, the NCAA divided Division I football into two subdivisions: NCAA Division I-A (known today as the Football Bowl Subdivision, or FBS) and Division I-AA (known today as the Football Championship Subdivision, or FCS).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The FCS adopted a single-elimination playoff structure to determine its champion, while the FBS retained its tradition of postseason bowl games.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Each bowl game was associated with a particular conference, and earning a spot in a major bowl game was the reward for winning a conference.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] This arrangement was beneficial to both conferences and bowl games, but it generally prevented the top-ranked teams from meeting in a true national championship game.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Because the NCAA itself does not officially sanction a Division I-FBS national champion, FBS national champions prior to 1992 were determined by polls, which frequently led to controversial or "split" national champions.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In 1992, the Bowl Coalition was created to determine the national champion.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] It was replaced in 1995 by the Bowl Alliance, which itself gave way to the Bowl Championship Series (BCS) in 1997.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] All three of these systems consisted of a single national championship game, as well as a set of other major bowl games.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In 2014, the BCS was replaced by the College Football Playoff (CFP), a single-elimination tournament.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In another major change, in 2021, following legal pressure and antitrust lawsuits, the NCAA and its conferences began allowing schools to offer compensation to student athletes for the use of their names, images, and likenesses (NIL).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] NCAA* allowed schools to directly pay players, ending the traditionally amateur nature of college athletics in the United States.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A football game is played between two teams of 11 players each.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Playing with more on the field is punishable by a penalty.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Teams may substitute any number of their players between downs; this "platoon" system has resulted in teams utilizing specialized offensive, defensive and special teams units.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The number of players allowed on an active roster varies by league; the NFL has a 53-man roster, while NCAA Division I allows teams to have up to 105 players on their roster.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Individual players in a football game must be designated with a uniform number between 0 and 99.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] NFL teams are required to number their players by a league-approved numbering system, and any exceptions must be approved by the commissioner.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] NCAA and NFHS teams are "strongly advised" to number their offensive players according to a league-suggested numbering scheme.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Women are eligible to play in high school, college, and professional football, but most football players are men.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] No woman has ever played in the NFL, but women have played in high school and college football games.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In 2018, women and girls comprised 0.5% of players in Pop Warner Little Scholars youth football, 0.2% of players in high school football, and 10.9% of Americans who report playing tackle football.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The role of the offensive unit is to advance the football down the field with the ultimate goal of scoring a touchdown.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The offensive team must line up in a legal formation before they can snap the ball.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] An offensive formation is considered illegal if there are more than four players in the backfield or fewer than five players numbered 50–79 on the offensive line.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Players can line up temporarily in a position whose eligibility is different from what their number permits as long as they report the change immediately to the referee, who then informs the defensive team of the change.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Neither team's players, except the center (C), are allowed to line up in or cross the neutral zone until the ball is snapped.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Interior offensive linemen are not allowed to move until the snap of the ball.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The main backfield positions are the quarterback (QB), running back (RB), and fullback (FB).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The quarterback is the leader of the offense.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Either the quarterback or a coach calls the plays.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Quarterbacks typically inform the rest of the offense of the play in the huddle before the team lines up.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The quarterback lines up behind the center to take the snap and then hands the ball off, throws it, or runs with it.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The primary role of the running back is to carry the ball on running plays.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Fullbacks tend to be larger than halfbacks and function primarily as blockers, but they are sometimes used as runners in short-yardage or goal-line situations.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The offensive line (OL) consists of several players whose primary function is to block members of the defensive line from tackling the ball carrier on running plays or sacking the quarterback on passing plays.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The most important role on the offensive line is the center, who is not just responsible for blocking and snapping the ball, but also for handling line adjustments and pre-snap strategy.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] On either side of the center are the guards (G), while tackles (T) line up outside the guards.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The principal receivers are the wide receivers (WR) and the tight ends (TE).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Wide receivers line up on or near the line of scrimmage, split outside the line.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The main goal of the wide receiver is to catch passes thrown by the quarterback, but they may also function as decoys or as blockers during running plays.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Tight ends line up next to the offensive line and function both as receivers and as blockers.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The role of the defense is to prevent the offense from scoring by tackling the ball carrier or by forcing turnovers.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Turnovers include interceptions (a defender catching a forward pass intended for the offense) and forced fumbles (taking possession of the ball from the ball-carrier).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The defensive line (DL) consists of defensive ends (DE) and defensive tackles (DT).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Defensive ends line up on the ends of the defensive line, while defensive tackles line up on the inside, between the defensive ends.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The primary responsibilities of defensive ends and defensive tackles are to stop running plays on the outside and inside, respectively, to pressure the quarterback on passing plays, and to occupy the line so that the linebackers can break through.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Linebackers line up behind the defensive line but in front of the defensive backfield.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] They are divided into two types: middle linebackers (MLB) and outside linebackers (OLB).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Linebackers tend to serve as the defensive leaders and call the defensive plays, given their vantage point of the offensive backfield.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Their roles include defending the run, pressuring the quarterback, and tackling backs, wide receivers, and tight ends.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The defensive backfield, often called the secondary, consists of cornerbacks (CB) and safeties (S).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties are themselves divided into free safeties (FS) and strong safeties (SS).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Cornerbacks line up outside the defensive formation, typically opposite a receiver to be able to cover them.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties line up between the cornerbacks but farther back in the secondary.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties tend to be viewed as "the last line of defense" and are responsible for stopping deep passing plays as well as breakout running plays.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The special teams unit is responsible for all kicking plays.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The special teams unit of the team in control of the ball tries to execute field goal (FG) attempts, punts, and kickoffs, while the opposing team's unit will aim to block or return them.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Three positions are specific to the field goal and PAT (point after touchdown) unit: the placekicker (K or PK), holder (H), and long snapper (LS).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The long snapper's job is to snap the football to the holder, who will catch and place it on the ground for the kicker.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] There is usually never a holder on kickoffs, because the ball is kicked off a tee; however, a holder may be used in certain situations, such as if wind is preventing the ball from remaining upright on the tee.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The player on the receiving team who catches the ball is known as the kick returner (KR).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The positions specific to punt plays are the punter (P), long snapper, upback, and gunner.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The long snapper snaps the football directly to the punter, who then drops and kicks it before it hits the ground.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Gunners line up split outside the line and race down the field, aiming to tackle the punt returner (PR)—the player who catches the punt.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Upbacks line up a short distance, typically 1-7 yards, behind the line of scrimmage, providing additional protection to the punter.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In football, the winner is the team that has scored more points at the end of the game.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] There are multiple ways to score in a football game.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The touchdown (TD), worth six points, is the most valuable scoring play.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A touchdown is scored when a live ball is advanced into, caught, or recovered in the opposing team's end zone.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The scoring team then attempts a try, more commonly known as the point(s)-after-touchdown (PAT) or conversion, which is a single scoring opportunity.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by a place kick or drop kick through the goal posts, it is worth one point, typically called the extra point.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by what would normally be a touchdown, it is worth two points; this is known as a two-point conversion.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In general, the extra point is almost always successful, while the two-point conversion is a much riskier play with a higher probability of failure; accordingly, extra point attempts are far more common than two-point conversion attempts.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A field goal (FG), worth three points, is scored when the ball is place kicked or drop kicked through the uprights and over the crossbars of the defense's goalposts.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Almost all field goal attempts are done via place kick.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] While drop kicks were common in the early days of the sport, the shape of modern footballs makes it difficult to reliably drop kick the ball.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The last successful scoring play by drop kick in the NFL was accomplished in 2006; prior to that, the last successful drop kick had been made in 1941.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] After a PAT attempt or successful field goal, the scoring team must kick the ball off to the other team.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A safety is scored when the ball carrier is tackled in the carrier's own end zone.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties are worth two points, which are awarded to the defense.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In addition, the team that conceded the safety must kick the ball to the scoring team via a free kick.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties are the least common method of scoring in football.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Football games are played on a rectangular field that measures 120 yards (110 m) long and 53+1⁄3 yards (48.8 m) wide.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Lines marked along the ends and sides of the field are known as the end lines and sidelines.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Goal lines are marked 10 yards (9.1 m) inward from each end line.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Weighted pylons are placed along each sideline, on the inside corner of the intersections with the goal lines and end lines.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] White markings on the field identify the distance from the end zone.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Inbound lines, or hash marks, are short parallel lines that mark off 1-yard (0.91 m) increments.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Yard lines, which can run the width of the field, are marked every 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A one-yard-wide line is placed at each end of the field; this line is marked at the center of the two-yard line in professional play and at the three-yard line in college play.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Numerals that display the distance from the closest goal line in yards are placed on both sides of the field every ten yards.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Goalposts are located at the center of the plane of the two end lines.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The crossbar of these posts is 10 feet (3.0 m) above the ground, with vertical uprights at the end of the crossbar 18 feet 6 inches (5.64 m) apart for professional and collegiate play, and 23 feet 4 inches (7.11 m) apart for high school play.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The uprights extend vertically 35 feet (11 m) on professional fields, a minimum of 10 yards (9.1 m) on college fields, and a minimum of 10 feet (3.0 m) on high school fields.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Goal posts are padded at the base, and orange ribbons are normally placed at the tip of each upright as indicators of wind strength and direction.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The football itself is a prolate spheroid leather ball, similar to the balls used in rugby or Australian rules football.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] At all levels of play, the football is inflated to 12+1⁄2 to 13+1⁄2 psi (86 to 93 kPa), or just under one atmosphere, and weighs 14 to 15 ounces (400 to 430 g); beyond that, the exact dimensions vary slightly.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In professional play the ball has a long axis of 11 to 11+1⁄4 inches (28 to 29 cm), a long circumference of 28 to 28+1⁄2 inches (71 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 21 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In college and high school play the ball has a long axis of 10+7⁄8 to 11+7⁄16 inches (27.6 to 29.1 cm), a long circumference of 27+3⁄4 to 28+1⁄2 inches (70 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 20+3⁄4 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Football games last for a total of 60 minutes in professional and college play and are divided into two halves of 30 minutes and four quarters of 15 minutes.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] High school football games are 48 minutes in length with two halves of 24 minutes and four quarters of 12 minutes.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The two halves are separated by a halftime period, and the first and third quarters are followed by a short break.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Before the game starts, the referee and each team's captain meet at midfield for a coin toss.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The visiting team can call either "heads" or "tails"; the winner of the toss chooses whether to receive or kick off the ball or which goal they wish to defend.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] They can defer their choice until the second half.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Unless the winning team decides to defer, the losing team chooses the option the winning team did not select—to receive, kick, or select a goal to defend to begin the second half.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Most teams choose to receive or defer, because choosing to kick the ball to start the game allows the other team to choose which goal to defend.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Teams switch goals following the first and third quarters.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] If a down is in progress when a quarter ends, play continues until the down is completed.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] If certain fouls are committed during play while time has expired, the quarter may be extended through an untimed down.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Games last longer than their defined length due to play stoppages—the average NFL game lasts slightly over three hours.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Time in a football game is measured by the game clock.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] An operator is responsible for starting, stopping and operating the game clock based on the direction of the appropriate official.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A separate play clock is used to show the amount of time within which the offense must initiate a play.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The play clock is set to 25 seconds after certain administrative stoppages in play and to 40 seconds when play is proceeding without such stoppages.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] If the offense fails to start a play before the play clock reads "00", a delay of game foul is called on the offense.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] There are two main ways the offense can advance the ball: running and passing.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In a typical play, the center passes the ball backwards and between their legs to the quarterback in a process known as the snap.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The quarterback then either hands the ball off to a running back, throws the ball, or runs with it.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The play ends when the player with the ball is tackled or goes out-of-bounds or a pass hits the ground without a player having caught it.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A forward pass can be legally attempted only if the passer is behind the line of scrimmage; only one forward pass can be attempted per down.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] As in rugby, players can also pass the ball backwards at any point during a play.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In the NFL, a down also ends immediately if the runner's helmet comes off.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The offense is given a series of four plays, known as downs.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] If the offense advances ten or more yards in the four downs, they are awarded a new set of four downs.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] If they fail to advance ten yards, possession of the football is turned over to the defense.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] In most situations, if the offense reaches their fourth down they will punt the ball to the other team, which forces them to begin their drive from farther down the field; if they are in field goal range, they might attempt to score a field goal instead.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A group of officials, the chain crew, keeps track of both the downs and the distance measurements.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The spot needed to secure a first down is known as the line to gain.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] On television, a yellow line is electronically superimposed on the field to show the line to gain to the viewing audience.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] There are two categories of kicks in football: scrimmage kicks, which can be executed by the offensive team on any down from behind or on the line of scrimmage, and free kicks.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The free kicks are the kickoff, which starts the first and third quarters and overtime and follows a try attempt or a successful field goal, and the safety kick, which follows a safety.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] On a kickoff, the ball is placed at the 35-yard line of the kicking team in professional and college play and at the 40-yard line in high school play.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The ball may be drop kicked or place kicked.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] If a place kick is chosen, the ball can be placed on the ground or a tee; a holder may be used in either case.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] On a safety kick, the kicking team kicks the ball from their own 20-yard line.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] They can punt, drop kick or place kick the ball, but a tee may not be used in professional play.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Any member of the receiving team may catch or advance the ball.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The ball may be recovered by the kicking team once it has gone at least ten yards and has touched the ground or has been touched by any member of the receiving team.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The three types of scrimmage kicks are place kicks, drop kicks, and punts.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Only place kicks and drop kicks can score points.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The place kick is the standard method used to score points, because the pointy shape of the football makes it difficult to reliably drop kick.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Once the ball has been kicked from a scrimmage kick, it can be advanced by the kicking team only if it is caught or recovered behind the line of scrimmage.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] If it is touched or recovered by the kicking team beyond this line, it becomes dead at the spot where it was touched.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The kicking team is prohibited from interfering with the receiver's opportunity to catch the ball.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The receiving team has the option of signaling for a fair catch, which prohibits the defense from blocking into or tackling the receiver.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The play ends as soon as the ball is caught, and the ball may not be advanced.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Officials are responsible for enforcing game rules and monitoring the clock.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] All officials carry a whistle and wear black-and-white striped shirts and black hats, except for the referee, whose hat is white.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Each carries a weighted yellow flag that is thrown to the ground to signal that a foul has been called.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] An official who spots multiple fouls will throw their hat as a secondary signal.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Women can serve as officials; Sarah Thomas became the NFL's first female official in 2015.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Another set of officials, the chain crew, are responsible for moving the chains.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The chains, consisting of two large sticks with a 10-yard-long chain between them, are used to measure for a first down.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The chain crew stays on the sidelines during the game, but if requested by the officials, they will briefly bring the chains onto the field to measure.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A typical chain crew will have at least three people—two members of the chain crew will hold either of the two sticks, while a third will hold the down marker.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The down marker, a large stick with a dial on it, is flipped after each play to indicate the current down and is typically moved to the approximate spot of the ball.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The chain crew system has been used for over 100 years and is considered an accurate measure of distance, rarely subject to criticism from either side.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Football is a full-contact sport, and injuries are relatively common.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur during training sessions, particularly ones that involve contact between players.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] To try to prevent injuries, players are required to wear a set of equipment.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] At a minimum players must wear a football helmet and a set of shoulder pads, but individual leagues may require additional padding such as thigh pads and guards, knee pads, chest protectors, and mouthguards.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur in the lower extremities, particularly in the knee, but a significant number also affect the upper extremities.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] The most common types of injuries are strains, sprains, bruises, fractures, dislocations, and concussions.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Repeated concussions (and possibly sub-concussive head impacts) can increase a person's risk in later life for CTE (chronic traumatic encephalopathy) and health issues such as dementia, Parkinson's disease, and depression.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Concussions are often caused by helmet-to-helmet or upper-body contact between opposing players, although helmets have prevented more serious injuries such as skull fractures.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] However, a study in the *Orthopaedic Journal of Sports Medicine* found that Heads Up Football was ineffective; the same study noted that more extensive reforms implemented by Pop Warner Little Scholars and its member teams were effective in significantly reducing concussion rates.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] A 2018 study performed by the VA Boston Healthcare System and the Boston University School of Medicine found that tackle football before age 12 was correlated with earlier onset of symptoms of CTE, but not with increased symptom severity.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] More specifically, each year a player played tackle football under age 12 predicted earlier onset of cognitive, behavioral, and mood problems by an average of two and a half years.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] To help mitigate injuries, the NCAA recommends limiting full contact (tackling to the ground) practices, avoiding full contact on consecutive days, and no more than 20 hours of practice per week.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p01] Players must receive one day off per week.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The National Football League (NFL) and the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) are the most popular football leagues in the United States.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The National Football League was founded in 1920 and has since become the largest and most popular sport in the United States.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL has the highest average attendance of any sporting league in the world, with an average attendance of 66,960 during the 2011 NFL season.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL championship game is called the Super Bowl, and is among the biggest events in club sports worldwide.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] It is played between the champions of the National Football Conference (NFC) and the American Football Conference (AFC), and its winner is awarded the Vince Lombardi Trophy.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] College football is the third-most popular sport in the United States, behind professional football and professional baseball, respectively.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The NCAA, the largest collegiate organization, is divided into three Divisions: Division I, Division II and Division III.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Division I is the highest level of play, while Division III is the lowest; Division I and II programs can offer athletic scholarships to student-athletes, while Division III programs cannot.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Division I football is further divided into two subdivisions: the Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) and the Football Championship Subdivision (FCS).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The champions of each level of play are determined through playoff systems.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Other national college football organizations include the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA), which comprises around 90 smaller colleges, and the National Junior College Athletic Association (NJCAA), whose membership consists of two-year colleges.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] High school football is the most popular sport in the United States played by boys.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The NFHS is the largest organization for high school football, with member associations in all 50 states as well as the District of Columbia.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] USA Football is the governing body for youth and amateur football, and Pop Warner Little Scholars is the largest organization for youth football.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The most successful league to directly compete with the NFL was the American Football League (AFL), which existed from 1960 to 1969.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The AFL became a significant rival in 1964 before signing a five-year, US$36 million television deal with NBC.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] AFL teams began signing NFL players to contracts, and the league's popularity grew to challenge that of the NFL.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged in the 1970 season, and all the AFL teams joined the NFL.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] An earlier league, the All-America Football Conference (AAFC), was in play from 1946 to 1949.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] After it had dissolved, two AAFC teams, the Cleveland Browns and the San Francisco 49ers, became members of the NFL; another member, the Baltimore Colts joined the league, but folded after just a year in the NFL.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Other attempts to start rival leagues since the AFL merged with the NFL in 1970 have been far less successful, as professional football salaries and the NFL's television contracts began to escalate out of the reach of competitors and the NFL covered more of the larger cities.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The World Football League (WFL) played for two seasons, in 1974 and 1975, but faced such severe monetary issues it could not pay its players.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] In its second and final season the WFL attempted to establish a stable credit rating, but the league disbanded before the season could be completed.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The United States Football League (USFL) operated for three seasons from 1983 to 1985.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Originally not intended as a rival league, the entry of owners who sought marquee talent and to challenge the NFL led to an escalation in salaries and ensuing financial losses.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] A subsequent US$1.5 billion antitrust lawsuit against the NFL was successful in court, but the league was awarded only $1 in damages, which was automatically tripled to $3 under antitrust law.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The original XFL, created in 2001 by WWE co-founder Vince McMahon, lasted for only one season.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Despite television contracts with NBC and UPN, and high expectations, the XFL suffered from low quality of play and poor reception for its use of tawdry professional wrestling gimmicks, which caused initially high ratings and attendance to collapse.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The United Football League (UFL) began in 2009 but folded after suspending its 2012 season after having lost $120 million over just three seasons.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Another spring league, the Alliance of American Football lasted less than one season, unable to keep investors.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] A revived United States Football League began play in 2022 and quickly faced immediate competition from the XFL, which resumed play in 2023.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged following the 2023 season, forming a new United Football League (UFL).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] American football leagues exist throughout the world, but the game has yet to achieve the international success and popularity of baseball and basketball.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] At the international level, Canada, Mexico, and Japan are considered to be second-tier, while Austria, Germany, and France would rank among a third tier.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] These countries rank far below the United States, which is dominant at the international level.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] NFL Europa, the developmental league of the NFL, operated from 1991 to 1992 and then from 1995 to 2007.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] At the time of its closure, NFL Europa had five teams based in Germany and one in the Netherlands.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] In Germany, the German Football League (GFL) has 16 teams and has operated for over 40 seasons, with the league's championship game, the German Bowl, closing out each season.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The league operates in a promotion and relegation structure with German Football League 2 (GFL2), which also has 16 teams.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The United Kingdom also operated several teams within NFL Europe during the League's tenure.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The resulting rise in popularity of the sport brought the NFL back to the country in 2007 where they now hold the NFL International Series in London, currently consisting of four regular season games.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The continuing interest and growth in both the sport and the series has led to the possible formation of a potential NFL franchise in London.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] NFL commissioner Roger Goodell aims to host 16 international games each year, enough for each NFL team to play one international game each year.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom, the British American Football Association National Leagues (BAFANL), an amateur competition, is the top level of American football.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Teams compete across multiple levels in a promotion and relegation structure; the league's championship is the Britbowl.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] University competition is held through the British Universities American Football League (BUAFL), which was formed in 2007.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] In 2008, the league launched a partnership with the NFL, through its partner organization NFL UK.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] From 2007 to 2014, the BUAFL grew from 42 teams and 2,460 participants to 75 teams and over 4,100 people involved.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The standard form of American football is not an Olympic sport, but it was a demonstration sport at the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The International Federation of American Football (IFAF), an international governing body composed of continental federations, received provisional recognition from the International Olympic Committee (IOC) in 2014 and was fully recognized by the IOC in 2015.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] American football federations are present in Africa, the Americas, Asia, Europe, and Oceania; a total of 75 national football federations exist as of 2023.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The IFAF runs tournaments such as the IFAF World Championship, the IFAF Women's World Championship, the IFAF Junior World Championship, and the Flag Football World Championship.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Obstacles towards the goal of becoming an Olympic sport included the predominant participation of men in international play and the short three-week Olympic schedule.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Large team sizes were an additional difficulty, due to the Olympics' set limit of 10,500 athletes and coaches.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] American football also faced an issue with a lack of global visibility.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Nigel Melville, the CEO of USA Rugby, noted that "American football is recognized globally as a sport, but it's not played globally." To solve these concerns, major effort was put into promoting flag football, a modified version of American football, at the international level.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Flag football for men and women will debut as an Olympic sport at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] "Baseball is still called the national pastime, but football is by far the more popular sport in American society", according to ESPN.com's Sean McAdam.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] In a 2014 poll conducted by Harris Interactive, professional football ranked as the most popular sport, and college football ranked third behind only professional football and baseball; 46% of participants ranked some form of the game as their favorite sport.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Professional football has ranked as the most popular sport in the poll since 1985, when it surpassed baseball for the first time.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Professional football is most popular among those who live in the eastern United States and rural areas, while college football is most popular in the southern United States and among people with graduate and post-graduate degrees.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Football is also the most-played sport by high school and college athletes in the United States.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] A 2022 survey from National Football Foundation found that one million high-school athletes played the sport, with another 81,000 college athletes across both the NCAA and the NAIA.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The Super Bowl is the most popular single-day sporting event in the United States, and is among the biggest club sporting events in the world in terms of TV viewership.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL made approximately $12 billion in revenue in 2022.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Super Bowl games account for eight of the top ten most-watched broadcasts in American history; Super Bowl LVII, played on February 12, 2023, was watched by a record 115.1 million Americans, and is second only to the Apollo 11 moon landing (125 million viewers).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL is the most valuable sports league in the world, with the average team valued at over $8 billion.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] American football also plays a significant role in American culture.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The day on which the Super Bowl is held is considered a *de facto* national holiday, and in parts of the country like Texas, the sport has been compared to a religion.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Football is also linked to other holidays; New Year's Day is traditionally the date for several college football bowl games, including the Rose Bowl.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] However, if New Year's Day is on a Sunday, the bowl games are moved to another date so as not to conflict with the typical NFL Sunday schedule.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Thanksgiving football is another American tradition, hosting many high school, college, and professional games.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Implicit rules such as playing through pain and sacrificing for the better of the team are promoted in football culture.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] In Canada, the game has a significant following.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] According to a 2013 poll, 21% of respondents said they followed the NFL "very closely" or "fairly closely", making it the third-most followed league behind the National Hockey League (NHL) and Canadian Football League (CFL).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] American football also has a long history in Mexico, which was introduced to the sport in 1896.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] It was the second-most popular sport in Mexico in the 1950s, with the game being particularly popular in colleges.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The *Los Angeles Times* notes the NFL claims over 16 million fans in Mexico, which places the country third behind the U.S. and Canada.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] American football is played in Mexico both professionally and as part of the college sports system.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] A professional league, the Liga de Fútbol Americano Profesional (LFA), was founded in 2016.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Japan was introduced to the sport in 1934 by Paul Rusch, a teacher and Christian missionary who helped to establish football teams at three universities in Tokyo.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Play was halted during World War II by order of Emperor Hirohito, but the sport began growing in popularity again after the war.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] As of 2010, there are more than 400 high school football teams in Japan, with over 15,000 participants, and over 100 teams play in the Kantoh Collegiate Football Association (KCFA).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The X-League is the largest American football league in Japan, and the largest American football league in the world to use a promotion-relegation system.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Some teams in the X-League, like the Panasonic Impulse, are sponsored by corporations, and all Japanese players on these teams are employed by the corporation.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The league operates in separate spring and fall seasons, with each team playing five games.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The top eight teams make the playoffs, which are played in Tokyo Dome; the champion is determined by the Rice Bowl.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Europe is a major target for the expansion of the game by football organizers.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom in the 1980s, the sport was popular, with the 1986 Super Bowl being watched by over four million people (about 1 out of every 14 Britons).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Its popularity faded during the 1990s, coinciding with the establishment of the Premier League—the top level of the English association football (soccer) league system.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] According to BBC America, there is a "social stigma" surrounding American football in the UK, with many Brits feeling the sport has no right to call itself "football" due to the lack of emphasis on kicking.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Nonetheless, the sport has retained a following in the United Kingdom; the NFL operates a media network in the country, and since 2007 has hosted the NFL International Series in London.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Super Bowl viewership has also rebounded, with over 4.4 million Britons watching Super Bowl XLVI.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The sport is played in European countries like Switzerland, which has American football clubs in every major city, and Germany, where the sport has around 45,000 registered amateur players.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] It was generally unknown there until the 1980s when a small group of players began playing on Copacabana Beach in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The sport grew gradually with 700 amateur players registering within 20 years.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Games were played on the beach with modified rules and without the traditional football equipment due to its lack of availability in Brazil.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Eventually, a tournament, the Carioca championship, was founded, with the championship Carioca Bowl played to determine a league champion.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The country saw its first full-pad game of football in October 2008.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] According to *The Rio Times*, the sport is one of the fastest-growing sports in Brazil and is almost as commonly played as soccer on the beaches of Copacabana and Botafogo.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Football in Brazil is governed by the Confederação Brasileira de Futebol Americano (CBFA), which had over 5,000 registered players as of November 2013.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The sport's increase in popularity has been attributed to games aired on ESPN, which began airing in Brazil in 1992 with Portuguese commentary.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The popularity and "easy accessibility" of non-contact versions of the sport in Brazil has led to a rise in participation by female players.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] According to ESPN, the American football audience in Brazil increased 800% between 2013 and 2016.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The network, along with Esporte Interativo, airs games there on cable television.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] NFL had expressed interest in having games in the country, eventually resulting in São Paulo's Arena Corinthians hosting Brazil's first NFL game in 2024, and the Super Bowl has become a widely watched event in Brazil at bars and movie theaters.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Further countries have also expressed interest in football to a lesser degree.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The Arab world has expressed growing interest in American football, with many countries in the region being members of IFAF Asia.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Jordan and the United Arab Emirates, which are not members of IFAF, have established their own domestic leagues.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Egypt established two leagues for the sport, namely the Egyptian League of American Football and the Egyptian Federation of American Football, and Saudi Arabia hosts two teams based out of Jeddah and Yanbu respectively.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] China has additionally been a target for the expansion of the sport, with the Mainland being the home of the Chinese National Football League as well as a growing audience of Super Bowl watchers.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Three franchises are also based out of Hong Kong, which prior to the COVID-19 pandemic regularly played mainland teams.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] NFL games average 900,000 viewers in China, though the league has cited logistical challenges which would prevent teams from playing games akin to abroad games in European countries.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Canadian football, the predominant form of football in Canada, is closely related to American football—both sports developed from rugby and are considered to be the chief variants of gridiron football.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The Canadian Football League (CFL) is the major Canadian league and is the second-most popular sporting league in Canada, behind the National Hockey League.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Football Canada is the governing body for amateur Canadian football, and is also member of the International Federation of American Football.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] NFL players have played in the CFL and vice versa; quarterback Warren Moon is the only player in both Canadian Football Hall of Fame and the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL and CFL had a formal working relationship from 1997 to 2006.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The CFL has a strategic partnership with two American football leagues, the German Football League (GFL) and the Liga de Futbol Americano Profesional (LFA).
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Rule changes announced in 2025 by the CFL will bring some elements of the sport closer to those of American football, while retaining the larger number of players, wider field, and three-down limit.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The Indoor Football League is an example of a prominent indoor league.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] The Arena Football League, which was founded in 1987 and ceased operations in 2019, was one of the longest-lived indoor football leagues.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] In 2004, the league was called "America's fifth major sport" by *ESPN The Magazine*.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Some schools that lack the enrollment numbers to run a competitive 11-man team choose to play nine-man, eight-man, or six-man football, which utilize modified rules to account for smaller team sizes.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] There are several non-contact variants of football, such as flag football.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] In flag football the ball-carrier is not tackled; instead, defenders aim to pull a flag tied around the ball-carrier's waist.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Flag football has become increasingly popular due to its lower likelihood of head injuries and its openness to female athletes; according to the NFL, which promotes flag football through NFL Flag, roughly 25% of flag football players are women and girls.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Another variant, touch football, simply requires the ball-carrier to be touched to be considered downed.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Depending on the rules used, a game of touch football may require the ball-carrier be touched with either one or two hands to be considered downed.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Wheelchair football is a parasport adapting the rules of football for people with physical disabilities.
[src:cue-sports/american-football-p02] Although it uses touch rules instead of tackling, wheelchair football isn't a non-contact sport; participants engage in both "big hits" and "physical blocks".
[src:cue-sports/american-four-ball-billiards] A variant of four-ball is the East Asian game *****yotsudama***** (四つ玉, Japanese for 'four balls'), or ****sagu**** (四球, 사구, Korean for 'four balls').
[src:cue-sports/american-four-ball-billiards] The game is played with two red object balls, one white cue ball and one yellow cue ball (or sometimes both cue balls are white, one having a red spot).
[src:cue-sports/american-four-ball-billiards] Each of the two players is assigned a white or yellow cue ball; whether the opponent can use it as an object ball is a difference between the Japanese and Korean versions.
[src:cue-sports/american-four-ball-billiards] A point is scored when the shooter caroms on two balls.
[src:cue-sports/american-four-ball-billiards] A carom on only one ball results in no points, and ends the shooter's inning.
[src:cue-sports/american-four-ball-billiards] A variation of four-ball called ***desítkový karambol*** (Czech for 'tenfold carom') is popular in Central Europe, especially in the Czech Republic.
[src:cue-sports/american-four-ball-billiards] It is played with white ball, a blue ball, a yellow ball and a red ball which serves as the cue ball for both players.
[src:cue-sports/american-four-ball-billiards] Players score a point by hitting two of the other three balls with the cue ball.
[src:cue-sports/american-four-ball-billiards] A carom off all three object balls in one shot, however, scores 10 points.
[src:cue-sports/american-four-ball-billiards] The score is doubled by hitting a cushion before hitting any of the other balls for a total of either two or 20 points in one shot.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The word *billiard* may have evolved from the French word *billart* or *billette*, meaning 'stick', in reference to the *mace*, an implement similar to a golf putter, and which was the forerunner to the modern cue; however, the term's origin could have been from French *bille*, meaning 'ball'.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The modern term *cue sports* can be used to encompass the ancestral mace games, and even the modern cueless variants, such as finger billiards, for historical reasons.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] *Cue* itself came from *queue*, the French word for 'tail'.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] This refers to the early practice of using the tail or butt of the mace, instead of its club foot, to strike the ball when it lay against a *rail cushion*.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] A recognizable form of billiards was played outdoors in the 1340s, and was reminiscent of croquet.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] King Louis XI of France (1461–1483) had the first known indoor billiard table.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Louis XIV further refined and popularized the game, and it swiftly spread among the French nobility.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] While the game had long been played on the ground, this version appears to have died out (aside from trucco) in the 17th century, in favor of croquet, golf and bowling games, even as table billiards had grown in popularity as an indoor activity.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In 1535, Mary of Hungary (governor of the Netherlands) played at a billiard table covered with green cloth in a gallery.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] James VI and I had a "bilzeart burde" covered with green cloth at Holyrood Palace in 1581.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The imprisoned Mary, Queen of Scots, had a billiard table at Tutbury Castle.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] She complained when her *table de billiard* was taken away (by those who eventually became her executioners, who were to cover her body with the table's cloth).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] A 1588 inventory of the Duke of Norfolk's estate included a "billyard bord coered with a greene cloth ... three billyard sticks and 11 balls of yvery".
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Billiards grew to the extent that by 1727, it was being played in almost every Paris café.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In England, the game was developing into a very popular activity for members of the gentry.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] By 1670, the thin butt end of the mace began to be used not only for shots under the cushion (which itself was originally only there as a preventative method to stop balls from rolling off), but players increasingly preferred it for other shots as well.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The footless, straight cue as it is known today was finally developed by about 1800.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Initially, the mace was used to push the balls, rather than strike them.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The newly developed striking cue provided a new challenge.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Cushions began to be stuffed with substances to allow the balls to rebound, in order to enhance the appeal of the game.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] After a transitional period where only the better players would use cues, the cue came to be the first choice of equipment.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The demand for tables and other equipment was initially met in Europe by John Thurston and other furniture makers of the era.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The early balls were made from wood and clay, but the rich preferred to use ivory.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The early croquet-like games eventually led to the development of the carom billiards category.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] These games are played with three or sometimes four balls on a table without holes in which the goal is generally to strike one *object ball* with a *cue ball*, then have the cue ball rebound off of one or more of the cushions and strike a second object ball.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Variations include straight rail, balkline, one-cushion, three-cushion, five-pins, and four-ball, among others.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In the United States, pool and billiards had died out for a bit, but between 1878 and 1956 the games became very popular.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Players in annual championships began to receive their own cigarette cards.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] This was mainly due to the fact that it was a popular pastime for troops to take their minds off battle.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] However, by the end of World War II, pool and billiards began to die down once again.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] It was not until 1961 when the film *The Hustler* came out that sparked a new interest in the game.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Now the game is generally well-known and has many players of all different skill levels.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The games with regulated international professional competition, if not others, have been referred to as "sports" or "sporting" events, not simply "games", since 1893 at the latest.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Quite a variety of particular games (i.e., sets of rules and equipment) are the subject of present-day competition, including many of those already mentioned, with competition being especially broad in nine-ball, snooker, three-cushion, and eight-ball.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Snooker, though a pocket billiards variant and closely related in its equipment and origin to the game of English billiards, is a professional sport organized at an international level, and its rules bear little resemblance to those of modern pool, pyramid, and other such games.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] A "Billiards" category encompassing pool, snooker, and carom has been part of the World Games since 2001.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Billiard balls vary from game to game, in size, design and quantity.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Russian pyramid and kaisa have a size of 68 mm (2+11⁄16 in).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In Russian pyramid there are 16 balls, as in pool, but 15 are white and numbered, and the *cue ball* is usually maroon or yellow.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In kaisa, five balls are used: the yellow *object ball* (called the *kaisa* in Finnish), two red object balls, and the two white cue balls (usually differentiated by one cue ball having a dot or other marking on it and each of which serves as an object ball for the opponent).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Carom billiards balls are larger than pool balls, having a diameter of 61.5 mm (2+7⁄16 in), and come as a set of two cue balls (one colored or marked) and an object ball (or two object balls in the case of the game four-ball).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Blackball (English-style eight-ball) sets are similar, but have unmarked *groups* of *red* and *yellow* balls instead of solids and stripes, known as "casino" style.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] They are used principally in Britain, Ireland, and some Commonwealth countries, though not exclusively, since they are unsuited for playing nine-ball.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The diameter varies but is typically slightly smaller than that of standard solids-and-stripes sets.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Snooker balls are smaller than American-style pool balls with a diameter of 52.5 mm (2+1⁄16 in), and come in sets of 22 (15 reds, 6 "*colours*", and a cue ball).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] English billiard balls are the same size as snooker balls and come in sets of three balls (two cue balls and a red object ball).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Other games, such as bumper pool, have custom ball sets.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Billiard balls have been made from many different materials since the start of the game, including clay, bakelite, celluloid, crystallite, ivory, plastic, steel and wood.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The dominant material from 1627 until the early 20th century was ivory.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The search for a substitute for ivory use was not for environmental concerns, but based on economic motivation and fear of danger for elephant hunters.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] It was in part spurred on by a New York billiard table manufacturer who announced a prize of $10,000 for a substitute material.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The first viable substitute was celluloid, invented by John Wesley Hyatt in 1868, but the material was volatile, sometimes exploding during manufacture, and was highly flammable.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] There are many sizes and styles of billiard tables.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Generally, tables are rectangles twice as long as they are wide.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Table sizes are typically referred to by the nominal length of their longer dimension.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Full-size snooker tables are 12 feet (3.7 m) long.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Carom billiards tables are typically 10 feet (3.0 m).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Regulation pool tables are 9-foot (2.7 m), though pubs and other establishments catering to casual play will typically use 7-foot (2.1 m) tables which are often coin-operated, nicknamed *bar boxes*.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Formerly, ten-foot pool tables were common, but such tables are now considered antiques.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] High-quality tables have a *bed* made of thick slate, in three pieces to prevent warping and changes due to temperature and humidity.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The slates on modern carom tables are usually heated to stave off moisture and provide a consistent playing surface.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Smaller bar tables are most commonly made with a single piece of slate.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Pocket billiards tables of all types normally have six pockets, three on each side (four corner pockets, and two side or middle pockets).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] All types of tables are covered with billiard cloth (often called "felt", but actually a woven wool or wool/nylon blend called baize).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Cloth has been used to cover billiards tables since the 15th century.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Bar or tavern tables, which get a lot of play, use "slower", more durable cloth.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The cloth used in upscale pool (and snooker) halls and home billiard rooms is "faster" (i.e., provides less friction, allowing the balls to roll farther across the table *bed*), and competition-quality pool cloth is made from 100% worsted wool.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Snooker cloth traditionally has a nap (consistent fiber directionality) and balls behave differently when rolling against versus along with the nap.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The cloth of the billiard table has traditionally been green, reflecting its origin (originally the grass of ancestral lawn games), and has been so colored since at least the 16th century, but it is also produced in other colors such as red and blue.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Television broadcasting of pool as well as 3 Cushion billiards prefers a blue colored cloth which was chosen for better visibility and contrast against colored balls.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] A rack is the name given to a frame (usually wood, plastic or aluminium) used to organize billiard balls at the beginning of a game.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] This is traditionally triangular in shape, but varies with the type of billiards played.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] There are two main types of racks; the more common triangular shape which is used for eight-ball and straight pool and the diamond-shaped rack used for nine-ball.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] There are several other types of less common rack types that are also used, based on a "template" to hold the billiard balls tightly together.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Most commonly it is a thin plastic sheet with diamond-shaped cut-outs that hold the balls that is placed on the table with the balls set on top of the rack.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The rack is used to set up the "break" and removed once the break has been completed and no balls are obstructing the template.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Billiards games are mostly played with a stick known as a cue.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] A cue is usually either a one-piece tapered stick or a two-piece stick divided in the middle by a joint of metal or phenolic resin.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] High-quality cues are generally two pieces and are made of a hardwood, generally maple for billiards and ash for snooker.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The *butt* end of the cue is of larger circumference and is intended to be gripped by a player's hand.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The *shaft* of the cue is of smaller circumference, usually tapering to an 0.4 to 0.55 inches (10 to 14 mm) terminus called a *ferrule* (usually made of fiberglass or brass in better cues), where a rounded leather *tip* is affixed, flush with the ferrule, to make final contact with balls.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The tip, in conjunction with chalk, can be used to impart spin to the cue ball when it is not hit in its center.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Cheap cues are generally made of pine, low-grade maple (and formerly often of ramin, which is now endangered), or other low-quality wood, with inferior plastic ferrules.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] A quality cue can be expensive and may be made of exotic woods and other expensive materials which are artfully inlaid in decorative patterns.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Many modern cues are also made, like golf clubs, with high-tech materials such as woven graphite.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Recently, carbon fiber woven composites have been developed and utilized by top professional players and amateurs.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Advantages include less flexibility and no worry of nicks, scratches, or damages to the cue.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Skilled players may use more than one cue during a game, including a separate cue with a hard phenolic resin tip for the opening break shot, and another, shorter cue with a special tip for *jump shots*.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The mechanical bridge, sometimes called a "rake", "crutch", "bridge stick" or simply "bridge", and in the UK a "rest", is used to extend a player's reach on a shot where the cue ball is too far away for normal hand bridging.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] It consists of a stick with a grooved metal or plastic head which the cue slides on.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Some players, especially current or former snooker players, use a screw-on cue butt extension instead of or in addition to the mechanical bridge.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Bridge head design is varied, and not all designs (especially those with cue shaft-enclosing rings, or wheels on the bottom of the head), are broadly tournament-approved.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In Italy, a longer, thicker cue is typically available for this kind of tricky shot.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Chalk is applied to the tip of the cue stick, ideally before every shot, to increase the tip's friction coefficient so that when it impacts the cue ball on a non-center hit, no *miscue* (unintentional slippage between the cue tip and the struck ball) occurs.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Chalk is an important element to make good shots in pool or snooker.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Cue tip chalk is not actually the substance typically referred to as "chalk" (generally calcium carbonate), but any of several proprietary compounds, with a silicate base.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Around the time of the Industrial Revolution newer compounds started to be used that provided better grip for the ball.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] This is when the English began to experiment with side spin or applying curl to the ball.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] This was shortly introduced to the American players and is how the term "putting English on the ball" came to be.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] "Chalk" may also refer to a cone of fine, white *hand chalk*; like talc (talcum powder) it can be used to reduce friction between the cue and bridge hand during shooting, for a smoother stroke.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Some brands of hand chalk are made of compressed talc.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Cue tip chalk (invented in its modern form by straight rail billiard pro William A.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Spinks and chemist William Hoskins in 1897) is made by crushing silica and the abrasive substance corundum or aloxite (aluminium oxide), into a powder.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] It is combined with dye (originally and most commonly green or blue-green, like traditional billiard cloth, but available today, like the cloth, in many colours) and a binder (glue).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Each manufacturer's brand has different qualities, which can significantly affect play.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] High humidity can also impair the effectiveness of chalk.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Harder, drier compounds are generally considered superior by most players.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] There are two main varieties of billiard games: **carom** and **pocket**.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The main carom billiards games are straight rail, balkline and three cushion billiards.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] All are played on a pocketless table with three balls; two cue balls and one object ball.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In all, players shoot a cue ball so that it makes contact with the opponent's cue ball as well as the object ball.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Others of multinational interest are four-ball and five-pins.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The most globally popular of the large variety of pocket games are pool and snooker.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] A third, English billiards, has some features of carom billiards.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] English billiards used to be one of the two most-competitive cue sports along with the carom game balkline, at the turn of the 20th century and is still enjoyed today in Commonwealth countries.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Another pocket game, Russian pyramid and its variants like kaisa are popular in the former Eastern bloc.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In straight rail, a player scores a point and may continue shooting each time his cue ball makes contact with both other balls.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Some of the best players of straight billiards developed the skill to *gather* the balls in a corner or along the same rail for the purpose of playing a series of *nurse shots* to score a seemingly limitless number of points.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The first straight rail professional tournament was held in 1879 where Jacob Schaefer Sr. scored 690 points in a single turn (that is, 690 separate strokes without a miss).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] With the balls repetitively hit and barely moving in endless "nursing", there was little for the fans to watch.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In light of these skill developments in straight rail, the game of balkline soon developed to make it impossible for a player to keep the balls gathered in one part of the table for long, greatly limiting the effectiveness of nurse shots.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] A *balkline* is a line parallel to one end of a billiards table.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In the game of balkline, the players have to drive at least one object ball past a balkline parallel to each rail after a specified number of points have been scored.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Another solution was to require a player's cue ball to make contact with the rail cushions in the process of contacting the other balls.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] This in turn saw the three-cushion version emerge, where the cue ball must make three separate cushion contacts during a shot.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] This is difficult enough that even the best players can only manage to average one to two points per turn.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] This is sometimes described as "hardest to learn" and "require most skill" of all billiards.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] There are many variations of games played on a standard pool table.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Popular pool games include eight-ball, nine-ball, straight pool and one-pocket.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Even within games types (e.g. eight-ball), there may be variations, and people may play recreationally using relaxed or local rules.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] A few of the more popular examples of pool games are given below.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In eight-ball and nine-ball, the object is to sink object balls until one can legally pocket the winning eponymous "*money ball*".
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Well-known but waning in popularity is straight pool, in which players seek to continue sinking balls, rack after rack if they can, to reach a pre-determined winning score (typically 150).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Related to nine-ball, another well-known game is rotation, where the lowest-numbered object ball on the table must be struck first, although any object ball may be pocketed (i.e., combination shot).
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Each pocketed ball is worth its number, and the player with the highest score at the end of the rack is the winner.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Since there are only 120 points available (1 + 2 + 3 ⋯ + 15 = 120), scoring 61 points leaves no opportunity for the opponent to catch up.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In both one-pocket and bank pool, the players must sink a set number of balls; respectively, all in a particular *pocket*, or all by *bank shots*.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In snooker, players score points by alternately potting *red balls* and various special "*colour balls*".
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Speed pool is a standard billiards game where the balls must be pocketed in as little time as possible.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Rules vary greatly from tournament to tournament.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The International Speed Pool Challenge has been held annually since 2006.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The game features both *cannons* (caroms) and the pocketing of balls as objects of play.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] English billiards requires two *cue balls* and a red *object ball*.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The object of the game is to score either a fixed number of points, or score the most points within a set time frame, determined at the start of the game.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Snooker is a pocket billiards game originated by British officers stationed in India during the 19th century, based on earlier pool games such as black pool and life pool.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The name of the game became generalized to also describe one of its prime strategies: to "*snooker*" the opposing player by causing that player to foul or leave an opening to be exploited.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] In the United Kingdom, snooker is by far the most popular cue sport at the competitive level, and major national pastime along with association football and cricket.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] It is played in many Commonwealth countries as well, and in areas of Asia, becoming increasingly popular in China in particular.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] Snooker is uncommon in North America, where pool games such as eight-ball and nine-ball dominate, and Latin America and Continental Europe, where carom games dominate.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The first World Snooker Championship was held in 1927, and it has been held annually since then with few exceptions.
[src:cue-sports/cue-sports] The World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association (WPBSA) was established in 1968 to regulate the professional game, while the International Billiards and Snooker Federation (IBSF) regulates the amateur games.
